node.text:
⚰️Funeral Friday⚰️
This photo shows an exhumed body which was used in a study to determine what kind of fungus grows on dead bodies. Fungal growth happens on both embalmed and unembalmed bodies. This research is helpful to people in pathology who have to sometimes perform autopsies on exhumed bodies. The study found the dead bodies commonly grew Aspergillus fumigatus and Candida albicans, both of which can cause lung irritation, especially to people with underlying lung disease. This is why it is recommended to use an N95 mask or other type of protective respirator while doing an autopsy of an exhumed body with visible mold growth. 
If you like cases like this, you will love The Gross Room!! More articles with photos/ videos, Celebrity Death Dissections, Quizzos and more!

node.text:
No this was not a piece of sausage!🤣
This patient was stung by an insect on the back of her arm. A nodule grew at the site where she was stung, so she went to get it looked at. She was given antibiotics and told to come back in 2 weeks if it did not improve. Over the next 3 weeks it did not improve and the nodule actually got bigger! Her doctor diagnosed her with a pyogenic granuloma. A pyogenic granuloma is a benign nodule that can grow rapidly, especially at the site of a bug bite. By week 7 the nodule grew to the size in this photo, 2” in diameter! She was sent to a surgeon to have it removed, who also thought based on the history that it was a pyogenic granuloma, but just to be sure he removed a little extra skin around it- in case it turned out to be something else. It did turn out to be something else, it was diagnosed as squamous cell carcinoma or skin cancer. This patient is fair with red hair, in her 50’s and had sunburns as a kid. She also has a history of using tanning beds in her 20-30’s. The background of her skin is very typical for “sun damaged” skin and when lesions occur in these patients skin cancer should always be a consideration. Photo: @spiritualinsights1111

node.text: The labia minora are the 2 inner lips (right and left) that surround the opening of the vagina. Both labia can be large and hang lower than the labia majora (outer lips). Other times the inner labia can be asymmetrical. This can not only cause self-consciousness about the appearance of the genitalia, but it can also cause extreme discomfort. This patient’s inner labia would fall outside of her underwear while cycling and would get stuck in her vagina during sex. Everyday her labia caused her discomfort, like chafing just from walking. She decided to have a procedure called a labiaplasty to remove the hanging tissue. She is expected to heal within 4-6 weeks where she can resume her normal exercise and sexual activity.

node.text:
This patient was in Hawaii for a wedding. She went swimming in the ocean and got what she thought was a little scrape on the top of her foot from coral on the ocean floor. The scrape started to get worse over the course of the next couple of days, but she did not seek medical attention because of the wedding activities. 2 days later, she returned from her trip and had to go right to work. At this point her foot was in so much pain she couldn’t keep it in a shoe. She was sent to the emergency room by her employer and there she was diagnosed with necrotizing fasciitis. Necrotizing fasciitis is commonly called flesh eating bacteria. This kind of tissue infection can be caused by many kinds of bacteria. When this happens, the bacteria release toxins that cause death to the skin and underlying tissue. This type of infection can get into the body rapidly so it is important that it is treated aggressively in a timely manner. Her doctors said she was lucky, if she did not come in when she did for treatment, she may have lost her foot and maybe even her life! 
Photo: @luv_me_doo

node.text:
When this patient was 15 years old, she went to the dentist to have multiple cavities filled. She was completely numb for the procedure. Suddenly her dentist said “hold on, don’t swallow” and reflexively the first thing she did was swallow! What she swallowed was a piece of a dental tool similar to a drill bit called a dental bur. She went to the emergency room and had this x-ray done that showed the dental bur. Doctors decided to monitor her and have her check her stools. She never found the dental bur but a follow up x-ray showed it was gone from her body! 
Photo: @cassidyonley
